var definitions = ['<h2>É o meu chapéu.</h2><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It denotes the existence or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese meaning "my". It indicates ownership and agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which in this case is masculine singular.</div><div><strong>chapéu</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "hat". It is a masculine singular noun and is the object of the sentence.</div>','<h2>O meu pai</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here in the masculine singular form to match the gender and number of the noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that means "my". It indicates ownership or relation to the speaker, also agreeing in gender and number with the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>pai</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "father". It’s a masculine, singular noun and the object of possession in this phrase.</div>','<h2>A minha casa nova</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It indicates a specific reference to a noun and agrees in gender and number with the noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This word is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "my". It indicates ownership or association, and it also agrees with the gender and number of the noun it is referring to.</div><div><strong>casa</strong> This is a common noun in Portuguese that means "house". It is feminine and singular in this context.</div><div><strong>nova</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese that means "new". It describes the noun by indicating a quality or condition. As an adjective, it must agree with the noun it modifies in gender and number, so here it is feminine and singular to match "casa".</div>','<h2>As minhas framboesas.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, the feminine plural form of "the". It is used here to specify the raspberries being referred to.</div><div><strong>minhas</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, the feminine plural form of "my". It indicates ownership of the raspberries by the speaker.</div><div><strong>framboesas</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "raspberries". It is the subject of the sentence and is in the plural form.</div>','<h2>Amo os meus pais.</h2><div><strong>Amo</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "amar", which means "to love" in English. It expresses an action or feeling by the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>os</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, masculine plural, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to specify the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>meus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, masculine plural, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or relation to the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>pais</strong> This is a common noun in Portuguese meaning "parents". It is masculine plural to match the possessive pronoun and the definite article.</div>','<h2>A tua mãe</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English when referring to feminine singular nouns or phrases.</div><div><strong>tua</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates that the following noun belongs to the person being addressed and agrees with the feminine singular form.</div><div><strong>mãe</strong> This is a common noun in Portuguese meaning "mother". It’s a feminine singular noun and is the object that is possessed as indicated by the possessive adjective.</div>','<h2>A tua melhor amiga</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the feminine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to specify a particular friend.</div><div><strong>tua</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates that the friend belongs or is related to the person being spoken to. It is in the feminine singular form to match the gender of the noun "amiga".</div><div><strong>melhor</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese, which translates to "best" in English. It is used to signify that the friend is the most excellent or closest compared to others. It is in the feminine singular form to agree with the noun "amiga".</div><div><strong>amiga</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "friend". It is in the feminine singular form, referring to a female friend.</div>','<h2>Tu estás tomando café em frente ao teu computador.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estás</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be". It indicates a temporary state or location of the subject.</div><div><strong>tomando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "tomar", which means "to take" or "to drink". In this context, it means "drinking". The construction with "estar"+gerund is used to describe an ongoing action, similar to the English present continuous tense.</div><div><strong>café</strong> This is a noun meaning "coffee" in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>em frente</strong> This is a prepositional phrase meaning "in front of" in English.</div><div><strong>ao</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "a" (to) and the definite article "o" (the), which in this case translates to "to the".</div><div><strong>teu</strong> This is the second-person singular possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "your". It indicates ownership or association with the subject.</div><div><strong>computador</strong> This is a noun meaning "computer" in Portuguese.</div>','<h2>Tu estás brincando com os teus brinquedos.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressed in an informal manner.</div><div><strong>estás</strong> This is the second-person singular form of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English, indicating a temporary state or location.</div><div><strong>brincando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "brincar", which means "to play" in English. In Portuguese, the gerund is often used with the verb "estar" to form the progressive aspect, which describes an ongoing action in the present.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "with" in English, indicating accompaniment or association.</div><div><strong>os</strong> This is the masculine plural definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>teus</strong> This is the masculine plural possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English when referring to multiple objects that belong to the person being addressed (informal second-person singular).</div><div><strong>brinquedos</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "brinquedo", which means "toys" in English. It refers to objects with which one plays.</div>','<h2>As tuas chaves estão no chão.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the feminine plural definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here to specify that the following noun is known to the speaker and listener.</div><div><strong>tuas</strong> This is the second-person singular possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It shows ownership or association with the person being spoken to, in the feminine plural form, as it’s modifying "chaves" which is feminine plural.</div><div><strong>chaves</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "keys". It is in the feminine plural form, corresponding with the definite article "as" and the possessive pronoun "tuas".</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural of the verb "estar" in Portuguese in the present indicative. It means "are" in English and is the verb in the sentence describing the state of being or location of the subject.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" meaning "in", and the masculine singular article "o" meaning "the". The contraction "no" translates to "on the" or "in the" in English. This indicates the location of the keys.</div><div><strong>chão</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "floor" or "ground". In this sentence, it indicates where the keys are located.</div>','<h2>O nosso novo apartamento.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It defines the gender (masculine) and number (singular) of the noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>nosso</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese meaning "our". It indicates ownership or association with the speaker and others included with the speaker. It also matches the masculine, singular form to agree with the noun "apartamento".</div><div><strong>novo</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "new". It describes a quality of the noun and agrees in gender and number with the noun "apartamento".</div><div><strong>apartamento</strong> This is a masculine, singular noun in Portuguese meaning "apartment". It is the object of description in the sentence.</div>','<h2>A nossa mãe é muito gentil.</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>nossa</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that means "our". It is in the feminine singular form to agree with the noun "mãe".</div><div><strong>mãe</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "mother". It is a feminine singular noun.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It is used here to link the subject "nossa mãe" with the adjective "gentil".</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in Portuguese. It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>gentil</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese that means "kind" or "gentle". It is in the singular form to agree with the noun "mãe".</div>','<h2>Estamos usando os nossos óculos.</h2><div><strong>Estamos</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It is used here to indicate a current, ongoing action.</div><div><strong>usando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "usar", which means "using". It follows the verb "estar" to form a continuous tense, indicating an action that is currently happening.</div><div><strong>os</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, masculine plural, meaning "the". It precedes the noun it’s referring to, in this case, "óculos".</div><div><strong>nosso</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, masculine plural, meaning "our". It indicates ownership or association with the speakers.</div><div><strong>óculos</strong> This is a masculine plural noun in Portuguese meaning "glasses".</div>','<h2>Estamos passando o dia com as nossas filhas.</h2><div><strong>Estamos</strong> This is the first-person plural of the verb "estar" in Portuguese, in the present continuous tense, meaning "we are". It’s used here to indicate an ongoing action that we are currently involved in.</div><div><strong>passando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "passar" in Portuguese, meaning "spending" or "passing" when referring to time. It works with the verb "estar" to form the present continuous tense.</div><div><strong>o dia</strong> This phrase means "the day" in Portuguese. It’s the direct object of the sentence, indicating what we are spending time on.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition meaning "with". It indicates the company or accompaniment in a particular action.</div><div><strong>as</strong> This is the feminine plural definite article "the" in Portuguese. It precedes the noun "filhas" to indicate specific daughters.</div><div><strong>nossas</strong> This is the feminine plural possessive pronoun "our" in Portuguese. It shows possession, indicating that the daughters belong to the speaker and possibly another person.</div><div><strong>filhas</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "daughters". It’s the noun and is in the feminine plural form to match with the article "as" and possessive "nossas".</div>','<h2>O vosso carro é muito legal.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "The" in English.</div><div><strong>vosso</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates that something belongs to the person being spoken to, and it is in the masculine singular form to agree with "carro". It’s also used in addressing more than one person (second-person plural), or in some dialects for a formal singular address.</div><div><strong>carro</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which translates to "car" in English.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "carro" with the predicate "muito legal".</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This word serves as an adverb in Portuguese and means "very" in English. It is used here to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>legal</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese that can mean "cool", "nice", or "legal" in the sense of being within the law, in English. Here, it’s colloquially used to indicate that the car is "cool" or "nice".</div>','<h2>Vamos acampar na vossa nova barraca.</h2><div><strong>Vamos</strong> This is the first-person plural form of the verb "ir" in the future immediate tense in Portuguese, which translates to "let’s go" or "we shall/will go" in English. It is used to express an intention or immediate future action.</div><div><strong>acampar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "acampar", which means "to camp" in English. It remains in its base form because it follows the conjugated verb "vamos".</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "a" (the), which together mean "in the" or "on the" when referring to feminine singular nouns in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>vossa</strong> This is a possessive adjective that means "your" in the context of addressing more than one person in a formal or polite way, or addressing someone in the second-person plural form. It’s related to the noun "barraca" that follows and agrees with it in gender and number (feminine singular).</div><div><strong>nova</strong> This is an adjective meaning "new" in English. In this sentence, it describes the noun "barraca" and agrees with it in gender and number (feminine singular).</div><div><strong>barraca</strong> This is a noun that means "tent" in English. Here, it is used to refer to the object the group of people will use to camp.</div>','<h2>Os vossos cachorros são lindos.</h2><div><strong>Os</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine plural nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>vossos</strong> This is a possessive determiner in Portuguese, reflecting the second-person plural ("your") and agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which is "cachorros" (dogs).</div><div><strong>cachorros</strong> This is a masculine plural noun in Portuguese, translating to "dogs" or "puppies" in English.</div><div><strong>são</strong> This is the third-person plural form of the verb "ser" (to be) in Portuguese, equivalent to "are" in English. It links the subject to the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>lindos</strong> This is a masculine plural adjective in Portuguese, meaning "beautiful" or "cute" in English, which is used to describe the dogs in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Nadei nas vossas piscinas.</h2><div><strong>Nadei</strong> This is the first-person singular form of the past tense for the verb "nadar", which means "to swim" in English. It indicates that the speaker swam.</div><div><strong>nas</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "as" (the), which are combined to mean "in the" when referring to feminine plural nouns in Portuguese. In English, it’s used to specify the location where the swimming took place — "in the".</div><div><strong>vossas</strong> This is the second-person plural possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English when addressing more than one person formally or familiarly in some Portuguese-speaking regions. It shows possession, indicating that the pools belong to the people being addressed.</div><div><strong>piscinas</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "piscina", which means "pool" in English. Here, it specifies the object where the action of swimming took place.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Onde fica o meu quarto?</h2><div><strong>Onde</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "where". It is used to ask for the location or place of something.</div><div><strong>fica</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ficar", which means "to be located" or "to stay". In this question, it’s asking about the location of something.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is the masculine singular possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "my". It shows possession, indicating that the room belongs to the speaker.</div><div><strong>quarto</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "room", particularly a bedroom or a private room.</div><div><strong>?</strong> This punctuation mark indicates that the sentence is a question.</div>','<h2>Onde está o meu livro?</h2><div><strong>Onde</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "where". It is used to ask for the location of something.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "estar" in the present tense, which means "to be" in English. It is used here to ask about the current location of something.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is the masculine singular possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "my" in English, denoting ownership or association to the speaker.</div><div><strong>livro</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "book". It’s a masculine singular noun, which is why it’s preceded by the masculine singular possessive adjective "meu" and article "o".</div><div><strong>?</strong> This indicates that the sentence is a question, seeking information.</div>','<h2>Era o meu aniversário.</h2><div><strong>Era</strong> This is the third-person singular of the imperfect tense of the verb "ser" in Portuguese, which means "to be". It’s used to talk about a past state or condition, similar to "was" in English.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes masculine singular nouns or phrases.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the speaker.</div><div><strong>aniversário</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which means "birthday". It refers to the anniversary of the day on which a person was born.</div>','<h2>Ele ficou com o meu dinheiro.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ficou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "ficar", which can mean "to stay", "to become", or "to end up", depending on the context. In this sentence, it means "ended up with" or "kept". It indicates what happened to the subject with respect to the money.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "with". It’s used here to indicate the relationship between the subject and the money.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s masculine and singular to agree with the noun it modifies, which is "dinheiro".</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates that the money belongs to the speaker. Like "o", it’s masculine and singular to match "dinheiro".</div><div><strong>dinheiro</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, meaning "money". It’s the object of the preposition "com" in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Eu estou comendo com o meu pai.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estou</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary state or location. It describes an ongoing action the subject is currently performing.</div><div><strong>comendo</strong> This is the present participle of the verb "comer", which means "to eat". In this sentence, combined with "estou", it forms the present continuous tense, indicating an action that is happening right now.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This word translates to "with" in English. It’s a preposition used to indicate company or association.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is here in the masculine singular form to agree with "pai".</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "my" in English. It’s used here to denote ownership or relation to the subject.</div><div><strong>pai</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "father". It’s the object of the preposition "com" in this sentence, indicating whom the subject is eating with.</div>','<h2>Sim, eu gostaria de saber o meu saldo.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It indicates an affirmative response or agreement to a statement or question.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gostaria</strong> This is the first-person singular conditional form of the verb "gostar", which means "to like" or "to appreciate". Here, it’s combined with "de" to express a polite desire, equivalent to "would like" in English.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition that, in this context, is part of the verbal phrase "gostaria de" forming the meaning "would like to".</div><div><strong>saber</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "saber", which means "to know" in Portuguese. It is used here to indicate the action that the speaker would like to perform.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article "the" in its masculine singular form. It indicates that a specific noun is being referred to.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is the masculine singular form of the possessive pronoun "my" in Portuguese. It denotes ownership or association with the speaker.</div><div><strong>saldo</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "balance", usually referring to the amount of money in a bank account or similar context.</div>','<h2>Hoje é o meu primeiro dia neste trabalho novo.</h2><div><strong>Hoje</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "today". It indicates the current day when the statement is made.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It connects the subject to its complement, indicating a state of being.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It specifies a particular noun that is known to the speaker.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is the masculine singular possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "my" in English. It denotes ownership or association with the speaker.</div><div><strong>primeiro</strong> This is a Portuguese ordinal number and adjective meaning "first". It defines the order of something in a sequence.</div><div><strong>dia</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "day". It’s used here to denote a period of time, specifically, the speaker’s first day.</div><div><strong>neste</strong> This is a contraction of "em" (in) and "este" (this) in Portuguese, together meaning "in this". It’s a prepositional phrase indicating location or position.</div><div><strong>trabalho</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "work" or "job". It refers to the speaker’s place of employment or occupation.</div><div><strong>novo</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "new". It describes the noun "trabalho" (job), indicating that it is recently acquired or started.</div>','<h2>Menti para o meu pai e não sei o que fazer</h2><div><strong>Menti</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "mentir", which means "to lie" in Portuguese. It indicates an action completed in the past, where the subject deceived someone by not telling the truth.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can mean "for", "to", or "towards" depending on the context. In this sentence, it suggests the direction of the action (the lie) towards someone (the speaker’s father).</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, translating to "the" in English. It is used here before "meu pai" to specify the father.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that means "my" in Portuguese. It denotes the relationship between the speaker and the subject mentioned, which is "pai" (father).</div><div><strong>pai</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "father". It is the person the speaker has lied to.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese equivalent to "and" in English. It is used to connect the two phrases within the sentence.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "not" or "no". It negates the verb that follows, which in this sentence is "sei" (know).</div><div><strong>sei</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "saber", which means "to know" in Portuguese. Here it expresses the speaker’s lack of knowledge or uncertainty about what to do.</div><div><strong>o que</strong> This is a phrase that means "what" in Portuguese. It introduces a direct or indirect question and is used here to express the speaker’s uncertainty.</div><div><strong>fazer</strong> This is an infinitive verb meaning "to do" or "to make" in Portuguese. It concludes the sentence, indicating the action that the speaker is uncertain about how to proceed with.</div>','<h2>Eu vim buscar a minha passagem.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>vim</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "vir", which means "to come". It indicates that the action has already happened, suggesting the "coming" is in the past.</div><div><strong>buscar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "buscar", which means "to fetch" or "to pick up". In this context, it expresses the speaker’s intention or purpose for coming.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for feminine singular nouns, which translates to "the" in English. It precedes and agrees with "passagem".</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which translates to "my" in English. It denotes possession, indicating that the passagem belongs to the speaker. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which is feminine singular in this case.</div><div><strong>passagem</strong> This Portuguese noun means "ticket" or "passage" in English. It is the object of the verb "buscar", indicating what the speaker has come to pick up.</div>','<h2>Eu dormia na minha cama.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dormia</strong> This is the first-person singular imperfect tense form of the verb "dormir", which means "to sleep". It describes a past continuous action or a habitual past action.</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) + the definite article "a" (the), which translates to "in the" in English. It is used to indicate the place where the action is happening. In this case, "na" is feminine singular to agree with "cama".</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "my". It indicates ownership and is feminine singular to match the noun "cama".</div><div><strong>cama</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "bed". It’s the place where the action of sleeping is taking place.</div>','<h2>Ótimo! É a receita da minha mãe!</h2><div><strong>Ótimo!</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "Great!" or "Excellent!". It’s an interjection expressing approval or satisfaction.</div><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It speaks about the being, existence, or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, in the feminine singular form, which translates to "the" in English. It is used here to refer to a specific recipe.</div><div><strong>receita</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "recipe". It is in the singular form and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a contraction in Portuguese, combining the preposition "de" (of/from) with the definite article "a" (the). Together they form "da", which translates to "of the" when conveying possession, and here it implies "my mother’s".</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese meaning "my". It is in the feminine singular form to match and agree with "mãe" (mother).</div><div><strong>mãe</strong> This is a feminine noun meaning "mother" in Portuguese. Here it refers to the speaker’s mother, whose recipe is being mentioned.</div>','<h2>Vou raspar a minha barba.</h2><div><strong>Vou</strong> This is the first-person singular of the verb "ir" in the future tense, which means "to go". Here, it’s combined with another verb to form a future action, equivalent to "I will" in English. In this sentence, it precedes the infinitive "raspar" to indicate a future action.</div><div><strong>raspar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb that means "to shave" in English. When combined with "vou" it translates to "I will shave".</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article "the" in English, used here for feminine nouns. In this phrase, it precedes "minha barba" to denote a specific beard.</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "my" in English. It is in the feminine form to agree with "barba".</div><div><strong>barba</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "beard" in English. It’s in the singular form and it’s the object of the action "raspar" in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Sim, aqui está o número da minha reserva.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It affirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>aqui</strong> This translates to "here" in English. It’s an adverb of place.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It refers to the location or temporary state of something.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>número</strong> This means "number" in English. It refers to a sequence of digits which denotes an identification, quantity, or order.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (of) and the definite article "a" (the), which translates to "of the" or "from the" in English.</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "my" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the speaker and agrees with the gender and number of the noun it modifies, in this case "reserva" (reservation).</div><div><strong>reserva</strong> This translates to "reservation" in English. It generally refers to a booking or an arrangement to reserve something (like a table or seat) for future use.</div>','<h2>Tenho poucas fotos da minha viagem.</h2><div><strong>Tenho</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter" in Portuguese, which means "to have". It indicates possession or a state.</div><div><strong>poucas</strong> This is the feminine plural form of the Portuguese word "pouco", which means "few" or "not many". It qualifies the noun "fotos", agreeing in gender and number.</div><div><strong>fotos</strong> This is the plural form of the Portuguese noun "foto", which means "photos". It’s the object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is the contraction of the Portuguese preposition "de" (from, of) with the feminine singular definite article "a", resulting in "da" which can translate to "of the" or "from the" in English. It indicates possession, belonging to something.</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is the feminine singular form of the possessive pronoun "meu" in Portuguese, which means "my". It agrees in gender and number with the noun "viagem" and indicates possession.</div><div><strong>viagem</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "trip" or "journey". It’s a feminine singular noun.</div>','<h2>A minha caixa é vermelha, a tua é verde.</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is the feminine singular possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "my". It denotes ownership or association with the speaker.</div><div><strong>caixa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "box". In this sentence, it is in its singular form and feminine gender, referring to an object that is owned by the speaker.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser" in Portuguese, which means "to be". It’s used here to link the subject to its attribute.</div><div><strong>vermelha</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "red". It agrees in gender and number with the noun it describes, which in this case is "caixa".</div><div><strong>a</strong> Here, this is again the definite article for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>tua</strong> This is the feminine singular possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "your". It indicates ownership or association with the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>é</strong> As before, this is the third-person singular of the verb "ser", meaning "to be".</div><div><strong>verde</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "green". Unlike English, Portuguese adjectives do not change according to gender, so "verde" can be used with both masculine and feminine nouns.</div>','<h2>Eu fui esquiar duas vezes na minha vida.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the Portuguese personal pronoun for "I", used as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fui</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "ir", which means "to go". It indicates that the action of going happened in the past.</div><div><strong>esquiar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to ski" in Portuguese. It is used after the verb "fui" to indicate the action that was performed.</div><div><strong>duas vezes</strong> This phrase means "twice" in Portuguese, indicating the number of times the action was performed.</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" and the definite article "a", which together mean "in the" in Portuguese, relating to time or place.</div><div><strong>minha vida</strong> This phrase means "my life" in Portuguese. "Minha" is the possessive pronoun "my", and "vida" is the noun "life".</div>','<h2>Ela está cantando a minha música favorita.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It describes a continuous state or action that is currently happening.</div><div><strong>cantando</strong> This is the present participle form of the verb "cantar", which means "to sing" in English. It is used with the verb "estar" to form the present continuous tense, indicating an action that is happening right now.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article "the" in Portuguese, used here before a feminine noun.</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "my" in English. It indicates possession or association with the speaker and agrees in gender with the noun it modifies, which is feminine in this case.</div><div><strong>música</strong> This is a noun meaning "music" or "song" in English. Here, it’s the object of the verb "cantando", representing what is being sung.</div><div><strong>favorita</strong> This is an adjective meaning "favorite" in English. It matches the feminine singular form of the noun "música" it qualifies.</div>','<h2>Sim. É um dos meus sonhos.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It affirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in English. It is used here to indicate a state of being or existence.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>dos</strong> This is a contraction of the Portuguese preposition "de" (of) and the masculine plural definite article "os" (the), translating to "of the" in English. It is used here to indicate a partitive relationship, as in "one of".</div><div><strong>meus</strong> This is the masculine plural form of the possessive pronoun "meu", which means "my" in English. It shows ownership or association to the speaker.</div><div><strong>sonhos</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "dreams". It is in the plural form, corresponding with "meus" to mean "my dreams".</div>','<h2>Tu verificaste o óleo do teu carro.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>verificaste</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense form of the verb "verificar", which means "to check". It indicates that the action of checking was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes masculine, singular nouns.</div><div><strong>óleo</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which means "oil". It is commonly associated with automotive lubricant.</div><div><strong>do</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (of) and the definite article "o" (the) in Portuguese. It translates to "of the" or "from the" in English and links the oil to the car in the sentence.</div><div><strong>teu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It’s used before masculine, singular nouns to indicate ownership. It’s the informal form of addressing someone in the second person.</div><div><strong>carro</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which means "car".</div>','<h2>É incrível que tu escondas isso do teu marido.</h2><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ser" in Portuguese, which means "to be". In this sentence, it functions as an impersonal expression equivalent to "It is" in English.</div><div><strong>incrível</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective that means "incredible". It describes something that is hard to believe or amazing.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that can be translated to "that". It introduces a subordinate clause, which in this case is "tu escondas isso do teu marido".</div><div><strong>tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>escondas</strong> This is the second-person singular present subjunctive tense of the verb "esconder" in Portuguese, which means "to hide". This tense is used to express doubt, possibility, or a subjective view.</div><div><strong>isso</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in Portuguese which means "this" or "that". It’s the direct object of the verb "escondas", referring to what is being hidden.</div><div><strong>do</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (from or of) and the definite article "o" (the) in Portuguese. It indicates possession or relation.</div><div><strong>teu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which means "your". It is in the masculine singular form to match "marido" (husband).</div><div><strong>marido</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese which means "husband". It shows the person from whom something is being hidden.</div>','<h2>Tu baterás no saco de pancada todos os dias no teu treinamento.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and typically used in informal situations.</div><div><strong>baterás</strong> This is the second-person singular future tense of the verb "bater", which means "to hit". It indicates an action that you will perform in the future.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) with the masculine singular definite article "o" (the), translating to "on" or "in the" in English.</div><div><strong>saco de pancada</strong> This is a compound noun meaning "punching bag". "Saco" translates to "bag" and "pancada" to "punch" or "hit", so together they refer to the bag that you punch or hit during training.</div><div><strong>todos os dias</strong> This is a phrase meaning "every day" or "daily". "Todos" translates to "every" or "all", and "dias" is the plural of "dia", which means "day".</div><div><strong>no teu treinamento</strong> This phrase consists of the contraction "no" again, here meaning "in the" when referring to a masculine noun, and "teu treinamento", which means "your training". "Teu" is a possessive pronoun equivalent to "your" in English (informal), and "treinamento" is a noun meaning "training".</div>','<h2>Espero que descubras coisas incríveis na tua viagem.</h2><div><strong>Espero</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "esperar", which means "to hope" in English. It indicates the speaker’s wish or desire.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word translates to "that" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>descubras</strong> This is the second-person singular subjunctive present tense form of the verb "descobrir", which means "to discover" in English. The subjunctive mood is used because the action is something the speaker hopes will happen, but isn’t certain.</div><div><strong>coisas</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "coisa", which means "things" in English. It’s the direct object of the verb "descobrir" (discover).</div><div><strong>incríveis</strong> This is the plural form of the adjective "incrível", which means "incredible" in English. It modifies "coisas" (things), describing what kind of things the speaker hopes will be discovered.</div><div><strong>na</strong> This contraction combines the preposition "em" (in) with the article "a" (the), translating to "in the" in English. In Portuguese contractions like this are common and depend on the gender and number of the ensuing noun.</div><div><strong>tua</strong> This possessive pronoun means "your" in English. It’s in the singular form and refers to something that belongs to the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>viagem</strong> This is a noun meaning "trip" or "journey" in English. It’s the object of the preposition "na", specifying the location or situation where the discoveries are to be made.</div>','<h2>Esqueceste o nosso compromisso?</h2><div><strong>Esqueceste</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense of the verb "esquecer", which means "to forget" in English. It is a question inquiring if the person has forgotten something.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese equivalent to "the" in English. It is masculine and singular, used here to define the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>nosso</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese meaning "our". It is masculine and singular, matching the noun "compromisso".</div><div><strong>compromisso</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese that translates to "commitment" or "appointment" in English. It represents an agreement or a scheduled event that one has agreed to.</div><div>The sentence as a whole "Esqueceste o nosso compromisso?" translates to "Did you forget our appointment?" or "Have you forgotten our commitment?" in English.</div>','<h2>Ficamos preocupados com o nosso filho.</h2><div><strong>Ficamos</strong> This is the first-person plural past tense form of the verb "ficar", which means "to stay" or "to become". In this context, it means "we became".</div><div><strong>preocupados</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "worried" or "concerned". It’s in the masculine plural form to agree with the speakers if they are assuming a masculine identity or if it’s a mixed group.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is the Portuguese preposition meaning "with". It indicates an interaction or connection.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, meaning "the".</div><div><strong>nosso</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "our". It agrees with the masculine singular noun that follows.</div><div><strong>filho</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "son". Combined with "o nosso", it translates to "our son".</div>','<h2>Nós temos pintado o quarto do nosso novo bebê por três horas.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>temos</strong> This word is a form of the verb "ter" in Portuguese in the first-person plural present perfect tense, which combined with the past participle forms a compound tense. Here, it expresses an action that has been happening.</div><div><strong>pintado</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "pintar" in Portuguese, meaning "painted". This is used together with the verb "temos" to form the present perfect continuous tense, indicating an ongoing action that started in the past.</div><div><strong>o quarto</strong> This phrase means "the room" in Portuguese. "O" is the masculine singular definite article "the", and "quarto" is the masculine singular noun for "room".</div><div><strong>do</strong> This is a contraction of the Portuguese preposition "de" (of/from) and the masculine singular definite article "o" (the). Together, "do" means "of the" or "from the".</div><div><strong>nosso novo bebê</strong> This phrase means "our new baby". "Nosso" is the masculine singular possessive pronoun for "our", "novo" is an adjective for "new", and "bebê" is the noun for "baby".</div><div><strong>por três horas</strong> This phrase translates to "for three hours" in English. "Por" is a Portuguese preposition meaning "for", and "três horas" is the phrase for "three hours".</div>','<h2>A nossa casa dos sonhos está lá.</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for the feminine singular noun that follows. It is equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>nossa</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese meaning "our". It shows ownership or relation to the speaker and others included in the conversation.</div><div><strong>casa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "house" or "home" in English.</div><div><strong>dos</strong> This is a contraction in Portuguese of the preposition "de" (of/from) and the masculine plural definite article "os" (the). It’s used here to mean "of the" or "from the" when referring to something that is plural.</div><div><strong>sonhos</strong> This is a plural noun in Portuguese that translates to "dreams" in English. Here, it refers to an idealized or desired type of house.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "estar" in the present indicative tense. It means "is" in English and is used to indicate the location or state of being.</div><div><strong>lá</strong> This is an adverb of place in Portuguese that translates to "there" in English. It indicates the location of the "dream house" mentioned.</div>','<h2>Nós enviávamos um presente aos nossos amigos.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>enviávamos</strong> This is the first-person plural imperfect tense form of the verb "enviar", which means "to send". The imperfect tense denotes a past action that was ongoing or repeated.</div><div><strong>um presente</strong> This is a phrase composed of an indefinite article "um" (a) and the noun "presente" (gift/present), equivalent to "a gift/present" in English.</div><div><strong>aos</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "a" (to) and the definite article plural "os" (the), equivalent to "to the" when indicating an indirect object in English.</div><div><strong>nossos amigos</strong> This phrase consists of the possessive pronoun "nossos" (our) and the noun "amigos" (friends), which together mean "our friends" in English.</div>','<h2>O professor poderá responder a todas as nossas perguntas.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>professor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "teacher" or "professor". Here, it refers to the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>poderá</strong> This is the third-person singular future indicative tense of the verb "poder", which means "to be able to" or "can". It indicates a future possibility or capability.</div><div><strong>responder</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese meaning "to answer" or "to reply". It is the action that the teacher can perform.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the preposition in Portuguese for "to", used here before "todas as nossas perguntas" to indicate direction or recipient of the action.</div><div><strong>todas</strong> This is the feminine plural form of the word "todo" in Portuguese, meaning "all" or "every". It qualifies the extent of the questions.</div><div><strong>as</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine plural nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>nossas</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese meaning "our". It specifies the ownership of the questions by the speaker and their group.</div><div><strong>perguntas</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "questions". It is what the professor will be able to answer.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);